{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"61da22f9-6a36-4a65-8702-cff0dc9042b0","content":"The directory is empty — there's no existing project yet. But I can answer your question directly:\n\n## Publishing a C# MCP server as a `dotnet tool`\n\nAdd these properties to your `.csproj` file:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <TargetFramework>net8.0</TargetFramework>\n\n  <!-- dotnet tool packaging -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata (required for nuget.org) -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <RepositoryUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</RepositoryUrl>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Key properties:**\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users invoke (e.g. `my-mcp-server`) |\n| `PackageId` | The NuGet package name |\n\n**Then publish:**\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org (get API key from https://www.nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n**Users install & run with:**\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's all that's needed — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the critical bits. The rest is standard NuGet metadata.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d4258b63-595f-4fb4-b54f-68e4470af1a1","outputTokens":542},"id":"27c0d0ee-7a1d-4b26-9a44-350ed65ebb4d","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:45:10.216Z","parentId":"ffb70c39-b690-4037-baa5-70119c11907e"}
